05745nam a2200649Ia 9781447300144DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20122012xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814473001447 a10.51952/97814473001442doi  a(DE-B1597)646546  a(OCoLC)802695068  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aEDU0340102bisacsh04a374.9400aLifelong Learning in Europe :bEquity and Efficiency in the Balance /ced. by Sheila Riddell, Jorg Markowitsch, Elisabet Weedon. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of figures, tables and case studies -- tNotes on contributors -- tList of contributors, by country, to the EU Sixth Framework Project ‘Towards a Lifelong Learning Society in Europe: The Contribution of the Education System’ (LLL2010) -- tLifelong learning and the generation of human and social capital -- tLifelong learning and the wider European socioeconomic context -- tNeoliberal and inclusive themes in European lifelong learning policy -- tFormal adult education in the spotlight: profiles, motivations and experiences of participants in 12 European countries -- tThe sociodemographic obstacles to participating in lifelong learning across Europe -- tThe qualification-providing enterprise? Support for formal adult education in small and medium-sized enterprises -- tReducing or reinforcing inequality: assessing the impact of European policy on widening access to higher education -- tConclusion: the role of lifelong learning in reducing social inequality at a time of economic crisis -- tTechnical annex to Chapter Four -- tGlossary of terms and abbreviations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe ongoing economic crisis raises fundamental questions about the political and social goals of the European Union, particularly the feasibility of harmonising social and education policy across member states. The forward momentum of the European project is clearly faltering, raising the possibility that the high water mark of European integration has been achieved, with implications for many aspects of education and social policy, including lifelong learning. This timely book makes a major and original contribution to the development of knowledge and understanding of lifelong learning in an expanded Europe. Its wide range of contributors look at the contribution of lifelong learning to economic growth and social cohesion across Europe, focusing its challenge to social exclusion. It draws on comparative data from the EU Sixth Framework Project Lifelong Learning Policy and Practice in Europe (LLL2010), which ran from 2005 - 2011 and involved twelve European countries and Russia. Very little research has been conducted to date on the nature of lifelong learning in post-Soviet countries, and this book provides important insights into their evolving education and lifelong learning systems. The book will be of interest to researchers and academics in the UK and Europe, especially those from social policy, adult and comparative education, equality studies and practice of lifelong learning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAdult learningzEurope. 0aContinuing educationzEurope. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / School Safety.2bisacsh1 aBoeren, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHefler, Günter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolford, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeuven, KU, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarkowitsch, Jorg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabular